The scribes of our MSS. shew themselves so ready to change archaic into more familiar forms (eg. isti Adv. into istim see note on v. 60), that it is only surprising that their evidence for istud, ista is not stronger. In no passage where the testimony of the Ambrosian Palimpsest is available, do we find these forms. Their occurrences are all in portions of the text for which we have the evidence of the Palatine MSS. alone, and even so, there is not a single one from that portion where the Palatine evidence is at its best (Persa-Prin.) Here are the instances where the MSS. (ie. the Palatine MSS. in the absence of A) agree in the reading istud (in Asin. 308 istuc DEJ, in Asin. 827 istuc D, istac J, in Aac. 418 istuc D) :

Asin. 644 Proinde istud facias ipse, quod faciamus nobis suades.

Aul. 490 Dotatae, si istud ius pauperibus ponitur (dotata es istud uis MSS. ).

Oapt. 898 A. I'Jnde id? B. A me meoque gnato. A. Sponden tu istud? B. Spondeo (sponde tu i. MSS).

Cist. 20 A. Amabo, hicine istud decet? B. Iusque fasque est. 27 Si idem istud nos faciamus, si idem imitemur, ita tamen uix uiuimus. 75 A. Veniet. B.
